**RARE, but part of an unprecedented invasion of this species into Massachusetts this spring. Up to four individuals have been seen: one adult in Duxbury, two adults in Wellfleet and this juvenile, found by Sam Bloch. He posted it on the Mass rare birds GroupMe and I rushed out to see it. Bird was on north side of Halcyon Lake at Mt Auburn Cemetery when I arrived. I didn’t see it initially, but was told it was on the near shore, and to view it near the Eddy Memorial. When I arrived, it had walked a bit closer to the Memorial. I observed it and photographed it for just a few minutes as it continued its trajectory around the pond, walking and feeding. After just a few minutes of observing, it flew across the pond, but without landing it gained altitude and seemingly flew out toward the Charles. Ryan Doherty and I searched for it at other likely sites in the cemetery without success. It was later relocated by Ted Bradford at Herter Community Garden (Boston) not far away.

On August 15th a non birding friend, Terri Hammond,  contacted me with a photo of a juvenile white ibis asking me to identify the bird. The ibis was observed and photographed by Terri and others, on August 14th. The ibis was on private property in a gated/posted community. I was given access by one of the property owners and asked not to publish the location or to bring others.  Large juvenile ibis with white abdomen, rump and underwing; pale neck and head;  brown back; long decurved pale bill; beige legs. The bird was first observed in a tree and then it flew down to the lake to feed. The ibis was observed feeding on aquatic vegetation.  Photos.  On August 23rd, I was unable to relocate the ibis at this location and areas in the immediate vicinity.

Observation Details: Found by Johnny Bovee on August 31. Adult with entirely white plumage, save for black tips to outer four primaries. Legs and feet bright pinkish-orange; bill relatively long and decurved, also bright pinkish-orange along with extensive facial skin on forehead and surrounding eye; iris pale bluish-white. Similar overall in size and shape to White-faced Ibis (direct comparison), but in flight showed slightly broader wings and only the feet projecting beyond the tail (portion of the legs and feet project beyond tail in WFIB), and also tended to sweep its bill from side to side when feeding unlike WFIB. The bird remained with the WFIB flock the entire time.

Observation Details: Easily my bird of the day. Juvenile, brown above with white undersides and dull pink decurved bill. The ibis was right at the westernmost hunting blind on the north side of the bay (the blind in with all the pickerelweeds). This area is only accessible by boat because I think it is technically a part of Ft. Belvoir. I must have rowed right past where it was perched because it flew in from behind me, parallel to the boat between me and the shore, and then landed in perfect view in a tree about 40 feet in front of me. I whipped out my camera and just sat there motionless while the sun set in front of me as the boat slowly drifted closer and closer until I was right under the ibis. All the while the bird was preening and stretching without a care in the world. Once it got too dark to shoot I rowed off while the bird settled in on that branch, probably to roost. An absolutely unforgettable experience. I believe this is the first record of one on the Mason Neck Peninsula. Also appears to be only the third county record outside Huntley Meadows.

**RARE, but part of an unprecedented invasion of this species into Massachusetts this spring. Up to four individuals have been seen: one adult in Duxbury, two adults in Wellfleet and this juvenile, found by Sam Bloch. He posted it on the Mass rare birds GroupMe and I rushed out to see it. Bird was on north side of Halcyon Lake at Mt Auburn Cemetery when I arrived. I didn’t see it initially, but was told it was on the near shore, and to view it near the Eddy Memorial. When I arrived, it had walked a bit closer to the Memorial. I observed it and photographed it for just a few minutes as it continued its trajectory around the pond, walking and feeding. After just a few minutes of observing, it flew across the pond, but without landing it gained altitude and seemingly flew out toward the Charles. Ryan Doherty and I searched for it at other likely sites in the cemetery without success. It was later relocated by Ted Bradford at Herter Community Garden (Boston) not far away.

Counted by 5s and 10s - flocks coming in from the NE and immediately gathering at the rookery. About 30-40% juveniles, and the percentage of juveniles in each flock increased toward sunset.  The previous NJ high count of White Ibis was 200, also at this location. This species is blowing up in southern NJ and DE, and was rare only 5 years ago! Tom Johnson returned the night after this (Aug 9) and got a more complete count totaling 1230 ibis, “Totals by age class: 450 juv, 177 SY, 603 adult. The largest flocks of WHIB (totaling 40-50% of all WHIB) arrived after sunset.”

Found by Johnny Bovee on August 31. Adult with entirely white plumage, save for black tips to outer four primaries. Legs and feet bright pinkish-orange; bill relatively long and decurved, also bright pinkish-orange along with extensive facial skin on forehead and surrounding eye; iris pale bluish-white. Similar overall in size and shape to White-faced Ibis (direct comparison), but in flight showed slightly broader wings and only the feet projecting beyond the tail (portion of the legs and feet project beyond tail in WFIB), and also tended to sweep its bill from side to side when feeding unlike WFIB. The bird remained with the WFIB flock the entire time.

Following up on Kyler's report from earlier today. We were westbound on Highway 230 and noticed a big flock of Ibises in the flooded UW Experimental Farm fields. Turned back to get a better look and saw a White Ibis resting and preening! All white with very light rusty stains and blue eyes. Pink-orange face, bill, and legs. Noticeably larger than all of the other Ibises. We both are pretty familiar with this species, having seen them around Florida as recently as this March. Really incredible to see just outside of Laramie!  On our way back (around 2:30 pm), it looked like most of the flock, including the White Ibis, was in the same field.

In habitat on nests nest building and mating. There were at least 1000 in the trees immediately adjacent to the highway; however, the tree grove is much deeper than we could access and we could see that there were thousands upon thousands more birds into the woods sitting on nests, nest building, and mating. Unable to count there are so many but there could easily be 100,000 birds in this colony. Amazing. Easy viewing from side of the road. Use caution on this busy highway. The males were flying across the highway to collect building materials, bringing sticks or soft green leaves back to the nest. Females sitting on the nests took the material and arranged within the nest. The male would cross his neck over the female to help. They would rub necks, seemingly hugging, singing or dancing, then off the male went to gather more materials and repeat. Eventually the male mounted the female to mate.

Locality: Key West Tropical Forest & Botanical Gardens

Observation Details: Easily my bird of the day. Juvenile, brown above with white undersides and dull pink decurved bill. The ibis was right at the westernmost hunting blind on the north side of the bay (the blind in with all the pickerelweeds). This area is only accessible by boat because I think it is technically a part of Ft. Belvoir. I must have rowed right past where it was perched because it flew in from behind me, parallel to the boat between me and the shore, and then landed in perfect view in a tree about 40 feet in front of me. I whipped out my camera and just sat there motionless while the sun set in front of me as the boat slowly drifted closer and closer until I was right under the ibis. All the while the bird was preening and stretching without a care in the world. Once it got too dark to shoot I rowed off while the bird settled in on that branch, probably to roost. An absolutely unforgettable experience. I believe this is the first record of one on the Mason Neck Peninsula. Also appears to be only the third county record outside Huntley Meadows.

Observation Details: White, long legged bird with black wing edges. Height about 2 feet. Bill long, pinkish and curved (down). Legs and feet also pinkish. Confirmation photos included.  Observed perched on a box elder tree that overhangs the Kewaunee River where it passes through my land (40 acres) here in Luxemburg, WI.  Perched about 3 meters above the river, probably fishing.  The river is flanked by old growth forest (both sides). River is about 15-20 meters wide where sighted. Max depth about 1-1.5 meters.  Originally I misidentified the bird as an egret, and did not consider it to be a notable sighting since this location is in the northern fringe of the egret's range. On 01/24/22 while reading an article titled "Along the Water's Edge" in the February / March 2022 issue of Birds and Blooms I discovered my mistake and properly re-identified it as a white ibis (both species were pictured on the same page).

*** Very rare, no previous records in eBird for Jefferson County or Kingbird Region 6. After trying to atlas in the rain for about 25 minutes I had just given up when I saw these two birds flying toward me. Based on their shape and rapid wing beats I immediately thought ibis, then as they passed me I noted their long decurved bills, mostly white underparts, and brown upperparts. I quickly made a U-Turn and followed them a short distance as they continued NNE, then they curved to the W and I thought I was going to lose them, but fortunately they wheeled around and landed in a large yard at the intersection of Farrell and Keyser Roads. I watched them forage for 6-8 minutes, during which time I could mostly see only one at a time while the other was obscured by veg. I noted that their bills were pale pink, their legs were grayish with maybe a hint of pink, and they looked overall brown, paler on the neck, except from certain angles when I could see white underparts. They moved out of view for a few minutes, then walked back into view right before taking off and flying to the N. I tried to follow them again but they quickly veered off to the WNW and flew out of sight.
A couple feeding in the surf like sandpipers on the incoming tide.

Observation Details: Every year at this time, when the water level in Holmes Creek drops enough that the flooded forest becomes exposed, and filled with trapped fish in small pools, hundreds of White Ibis appear to rest and feed!  Today there were 250 of them out here!  They probe the mud with their long bills.  When they fly they look like angels!  They have odd, pig-like calls!  The Holmes Creek river gauge was at 13.0’.

Observed White Ibis foraging for food in shallow waters about 30 feet from the road.  The bird was not too skittish.  At times he would stop and stare at us and then continue walking slowly away from us through the water and reeds, stopping to forage for food.  At one point he flew up and landed in heavy reeds about 50 feet away.  The black-tipped wings were visible in flight.  We drove away and on our return to the same spot 10 minutes later the bird was observed again in almost the same spot it was first observed.  Again, walking slowly, keeping an eye on us and foraging for food.  Due to the reddish/pink coloring of his bill and legs appears to be a male.

Observation Details: Easily my bird of the day. Juvenile, brown above with white undersides and dull pink decurved bill. The ibis was right at the westernmost hunting blind on the north side of the bay (the blind in with all the pickerelweeds). This area is only accessible by boat because I think it is technically a part of Ft. Belvoir. I must have rowed right past where it was perched because it flew in from behind me, parallel to the boat between me and the shore, and then landed in perfect view in a tree about 40 feet in front of me. I whipped out my camera and just sat there motionless while the sun set in front of me as the boat slowly drifted closer and closer until I was right under the ibis. All the while the bird was preening and stretching without a care in the world. Once it got too dark to shoot I rowed off while the bird settled in on that branch, probably to roost. An absolutely unforgettable experience. I believe this is the first record of one on the Mason Neck Peninsula. Also appears to be only the third county record outside Huntley Meadows.

**rare breeder, first confirmed nesting record for the state. Same pair of adults we had yesterday but couldn't confirm. Nest was about 15 feet up in a huge tangle of blackberry and honey suckle grown up around a little cherry tree. Nest site was like a shallow circular tunnel carved into the side of the bushes with the actual nest in the opening. Nest was generally away from all the GLIB nests but near some LBHE, TRHE, SNEG, and BCNH. Could see 3 young in the nest and the adults went in to presumably feed them a few times. Photos.

Locality: Reserva de la Biosfera de Sian Ka'an

Observation Details: Found by Johnny Bovee on August 31. Adult with entirely white plumage, save for black tips to outer four primaries. Legs and feet bright pinkish-orange; bill relatively long and decurved, also bright pinkish-orange along with extensive facial skin on forehead and surrounding eye; iris pale bluish-white. Similar overall in size and shape to White-faced Ibis (direct comparison), but in flight showed slightly broader wings and only the feet projecting beyond the tail (portion of the legs and feet project beyond tail in WFIB), and also tended to sweep its bill from side to side when feeding unlike WFIB. The bird remained with the WFIB flock the entire time.

Observation Details: Counted by 5s and 10s - flocks coming in from the NE and immediately gathering at the rookery. About 30-40% juveniles, and the percentage of juveniles in each flock increased toward sunset.  The previous NJ high count of White Ibis was 200, also at this location. This species is blowing up in southern NJ and DE, and was rare only 5 years ago! Tom Johnson returned the night after this (Aug 9) and got a more complete count totaling 1230 ibis, “Totals by age class: 450 juv, 177 SY, 603 adult. The largest flocks of WHIB (totaling 40-50% of all WHIB) arrived after sunset.”

**rare breeder, first confirmed nesting record for the state. Same pair of adults we had yesterday but couldn't confirm. Nest was about 15 feet up in a huge tangle of blackberry and honey suckle grown up around a little cherry tree. Nest site was like a shallow circular tunnel carved into the side of the bushes with the actual nest in the opening. Nest was generally away from all the GLIB nests but right with a bunch of LBHE, TRHE, SNEG, and BCNH. Saw 3 young in the nest and the adults went in to presumably feed them a few times. Photos of adults and young.

The Holmes Creek river gauge was at 13.0’.

Rare; continuing juveniles at the pond. Warm brown back, white below, pale head and neck, and long decurved bill with transitional colors (bright red at bottom base of bill, rest mostly orangish with some gray), pale legs. One showed up around 12:10 pm on the NE side (spotted by Mary Beth), and after several minutes it flew off, circled over us and eventually landed in a tree near the the SW corner of the pond (relocated by Sean). It stayed in the tree for ten minutes or so looking somewhat nervous, then flew down to the SE side. After that it comfortably stayed there feeding & preening with a few GLIB, SNEG and YCNH. Two more flew in around 1:20 pm and landed at the NE side (spotted by Karen).  All three birds were still present at the same locations when we left around 1:45 pm.  Photos and video.

Immature birds showing a white breast and sides when they flapped their brown wings. Flew back and forth from the pond to the marsh where they could be viewed from the platform. Nothing like an uncommon bird for the area to bring out the MOB.

Observation Details: Both juvenile.

A trio of juvenile WHIB landed along the creek edge as I was heading back to the hill of life dam from upstream. I watched them forage downstream when I got to the dam, and they approached very close. In contrast to the Limpkin, the ibises actively pick tiny insects and cricket frogs off the creekside mud and probe the crevices of rocks with their thin bills rather than cracking the shells of mollusks. A few had the first white feathers growing on the wing coverts

Walking upstream from the hill of life, a WHIB flew up from one of the remaining stagnant puddles of the creek. It landed up high in dead branches and was too wary to fly back down before I walked away. The drying creek bed has attracted a surprise variety of wading birds to the greenbelt this year

Observation Details: White, long legged bird with black wing edges. Height about 2 feet. Bill long, pinkish and curved (down). Legs and feet also pinkish. Confirmation photos included.  Observed perched on a box elder tree that overhangs the Kewaunee River where it passes through my land (40 acres) here in Luxemburg, WI.  Perched about 3 meters above the river, probably fishing.  The river is flanked by old growth forest (both sides). River is about 15-20 meters wide where sighted. Max depth about 1-1.5 meters.  Originally I misidentified the bird as an egret, and did not consider it to be a notable sighting since this location is in the northern fringe of the egret's range. On 01/24/22 while reading an article titled "Along the Water's Edge" in the February / March 2022 issue of Birds and Blooms I discovered my mistake and properly re-identified it as a white ibis (both species were pictured on the same page).

Observation Details: Continuing immature found August 22 by Dean Newhouse. The bird was sleeping on the close island in the cove, then began foraging along its shore. It eventually flew to the dam shoreline before returning to the main cove. It blended in remarkably well on the island.

Easily my bird of the day. Juvenile, brown above with white undersides and dull pink decurved bill. The ibis was right at the westernmost hunting blind on the north side of the bay (the blind in with all the pickerelweeds). This area is only accessible by boat because I think it is technically a part of Ft. Belvoir. I must have rowed right past where it was perched because it flew in from behind me, parallel to the boat between me and the shore, and then landed in perfect view in a tree about 40 feet in front of me. I whipped out my camera and just sat there motionless while the sun set in front of me as the boat slowly drifted closer and closer until I was right under the ibis. All the while the bird was preening and stretching without a care in the world. Once it got too dark to shoot I rowed off while the bird settled in on that branch, probably to roost. An absolutely unforgettable experience. I believe this is the first record of one on the Mason Neck Peninsula. Also appears to be only the third county record outside Huntley Meadows.
